<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-810-680  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 810 680.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 3 1990 v9 n18 p26(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>12 govt. agencies are taking part in CD-ROM expo. (Fed Micro '90'sspecial show on CD-ROM)andM;</TITLE><SUMMARY>The Fed Micro '90 convention to take place in Washington DC on Sep5 and 6 will for the first time include a special mini-conventionon CD-ROM technology.andP;  Twelve government agencies will demonstratetheir usage or publication of CD-ROM disks in an ApplicationsCenter to be located on the floor of the exposition.andP;  An annualaward will be initiated to honor the agency that has made the mostuseful contribution to the public dissemination of governmentinformation on CD-ROM.andP;  Tax savings, affordability,user-friendliness and contribution to the public good will beamong the factors considered by judges.andP;  The CD-ROM conference issponsored by FOSE, the sister show to Fed Micro.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Conferences and MeetingsPublicationsApplicationsMicrocomputersCD-ROMGovernment AgencyProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   CD-ROM exhibitors. (table)How-to workshops for managers and advanced users. (table)Fed Micro conference schedule. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>12 Govt.andP;  Agencies Are Taking Part in CE-ROM ExpoandM;Fed Micro this year will have a n ew show-within-a-show featuring CD-ROMtechnology.andP;  Twelve government agencies will participate in the exposition,in conjunction with the Special Interest Group on CD-ROM Applications andTechnology (SIGCAT).andM;The new CD-ROM conference and exposition is sponsored by Fed Micro's sistershow, FOSE, which takes place in Washington in the spring.andM;The 12 agencies will demonstrate how they use and publish CD-ROMs in aspecial CD-ROM Applications Center located on the exposition floor.andM;Fed Micro also will present an award to the agency judged to have made themost significant contribution to public dissemination of governmentinformation on CD-ROM.andM;This award, the first in a planned annual series of FOSE CD-ROM awards, willbe announced during the first conference session.andP;  The judging criteriainclude saving tax dollars, contributing to the public good, producing anaffordable product and providing a friendly user interface.andM;CD-ROM conference session run from 8:30 a.m.andP;  to 4:15 p.m.andP;  each day of FedMicro.andP;  The CD-ROM exposition is open from 10 a.m.andP;  to 4 p.m.andP;  each day.andM;On Wednesday, Sept. 5, beginning at 1 p.m., the Patent and Trademark Office,National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and Agriculture Departmentwill present half-hour demonstrations.andM;Wednesday afternoon beginning at 2:45 p.m., the Defense Mapping Agency,Library of Congress and Census Bureau will give half-hour presentations.andM;On Tuesday, Sept. 6, the Commerce Department, NASA and Geological Survey havea half-hour demonstrations beginning at 8:30 a.m., followed at 10:15 a.m.andP;  bythe Housing and Urban Development Department, Environmental Protection Agencyand Defense General Supply Center.andM;Among the other scheduled events on Wednesday are introductory CD-ROMsessions and case studies from 8:30 to 11:15 a.m.andM;On Thursday, the Special Interest Group for Optical Media in Education andTraining will present a session on the emerging multimedia opticaltechnologies.andM;These and other applications briefings will take place in the CD-ROMApplications Center on the exposition floor.andM;CD-ROM vendors in the Applications Center plan to display software, internaland external drives, disk storage devices, optical information retrievalsystems and interfaces.andM;Vendors of formatting, mastering and replication services also will take partin the show.andM;Each person who attends the FOSE CD-ROM conference will receive a freecompendium of CD-ROM titles produced by the Geological Survey Library andSIGCAT.andP;  The compendium describes disks produced by agencies and privateorganizations, and gives ordering information.andM;Vendors will present several briefings.andP;  A session at 1 p.m.andP;  Wednesday byMeridian Data Inc. will cover CD-ROM networking, multimedia, image capturetools and the Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support effort.andM;At 11 a.m.andP;  Thursday, Knowledge Access International Inc. will hold abriefing on CD-ROM publishing.andP;  At 1 p.m., Pioneer Communications of AmericaInc. has scheduled a briefing on minichanger applications.andO;</TEXT></DOC>